result.execSummary:
The defendant Timothy Earl Everson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Escape, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.42(3)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

civilJdgmts.propDescr: Unpaid Court Ordered Financial Obligations Converted to a Civil Judgment

supervisions.notes: Defendant to receive 34 days jail credit if revoked in the future.  In the event that the defendant is discharged from probation with outstanding financial obligations, the supervising agent SHALL notify the court 10 days prior to the revocation or discharge.  A civil judgment SHALL be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt.

miscConds.notes: Restitution of $284.00 due Trempealeau County, surcharge of $28.40 owed to District Attorney's Office.  Defendant shall set up pay plan with DOC.
Defendant may apply for expungement if he successfully completes probation without any new offenses or serious violations.

Defendant shall provide a DNA sample.  Defendant shall write apology letter to the Trempealeau County Clerk and to the employees of Trempealeau County.  Apology letter shall be submitted to the Probation Agent when requested.  Defendant shall complete a risk and needs assessment, sign all necessary releases and follow the Probation Agent's recommendations.

timeConds.notes: IMPOSED AND STAYED as long as defendant goes to and completes inpatient treatment program at Fahrman Center.
